

NXC: Neural-network XC utilities for SIESTA (NN-GGA, non spin-polarized)
======================================================================

This directory contains helper scripts to export trained JAX/Equinox neural-network
GGA XC models (Fx and Fc) into ASCII parameter files that are read by the NN-enabled
SIESTA build.

The current NNXC implementation is:
  - GGA only (depends on rho and |grad rho|)
  - non spin-polarized (SpinPolarized = false)

The NN provides enhancement factors Fx(rho,|∇rho|) and Fc(rho,|∇rho|) which are
combined inside SIESTA with SIESTA’s own LDA references:
  - exchange: EXCHNG (LDA-x)
  - correlation: PW92C (PW92 LDA-c)

NNXC utilities for SIESTA
========================

This directory contains utilities to export trained JAX/Equinox NNXC models
into ASCII files readable by the NNXC-enabled SIESTA code.

The intended workflow is:
  1. Train NNXC models in JAX/Equinox.
  2. Export the trained models to per-layer ASCII files.
  3. Point SIESTA to the exported parameter prefix.


1. Directory contents
---------------------

Typical files and directories:

  export_eqx_to_fortran.py
    Python script that loads Equinox models and writes per-layer ASCII files
    (weights and biases).

  export_nnxc.sh
    Wrapper script (recommended entry point) that:
      - validates inputs
      - calls the Python exporter
      - stages output files into nn_params/

  nnxc_tools_pkg/
    Python package providing shared NNXC utilities (model loading, parameter
    extraction). This package must be installed once in your Python environment.

  nn_params/
    Destination directory containing exported ASCII NNXC parameters for SIESTA.

  Sample-Models/
    Example trained NNXC models (.eqx + .json).

  Sample_SiestaRuns/
    Example SIESTA input files using NNXC.


2. Prerequisites
----------------

Python environment:
  - Python 3.10+ (tested with 3.10–3.13)
  - numpy
  - jax, jaxlib
  - equinox

Install the shared NNXC utilities once:

  cd Util/NXC/nnxc_tools_pkg
  python -m pip install -e .

Verify installation:

  python -c "import nnxc_tools; print(nnxc_tools.__file__)"

This should print a path inside nnxc_tools_pkg/nnxc_tools/.

SIESTA build:
  - Use the NNXC-enabled SIESTA build in this repository.
  - The build must include the NNXC modules in SiestaXC.


3. Model file format
--------------------

Each trained model is expected to exist as two files sharing a prefix:

  <MODEL_PREFIX>.eqx    (Equinox serialized parameters)
  <MODEL_PREFIX>.json   (Model metadata / architecture)

Example:

  Sample-Models/pretrainedinSiesta/
    GGA_Fx_G_transf_lin_d3_n16_s42_v_20000.eqx
    GGA_Fx_G_transf_lin_d3_n16_s42_v_20000.json

IMPORTANT:
  When exporting, always pass the prefix only.
  Do NOT include .eqx or .json in the command-line arguments.


4. Exporting NNXC models (recommended)
--------------------------------------

Run the exporter from this directory:

  ./export_nnxc.sh \
    --fx-model Sample-Models/pretrainedinSiesta/GGA_Fx_G_transf_lin_d3_n16_s42_v_20000 \
    --fc-model Sample-Models/pretrainedinSiesta/GGA_Fc_G_transf_lin_d3_n16_s42_v_20000 \
    --out-prefix xc_nn

This will:
  1. Load the Fx and Fc Equinox models
  2. Extract MLP weights and biases
  3. Write ASCII files
  4. Stage them into:

    ./nn_params/

Resulting files:

  nn_params/
    xc_nn_fx_W1.dat  xc_nn_fx_b1.dat
    ...
    xc_nn_fc_W4.dat  xc_nn_fc_b4.dat


5. Use in siesta
---------------------------

currently, to use the NN xc in siesta only works with these labels:
XC.functional   GGA
XC.authors      NNGGA

This expects to find inside the running directory the nn_params/ directory
generated in the previous step. Unfortunatelly the name of the directory
is rigid so care must be taken not to use the wrong NN parameters.

6. Notes and common pitfalls
----------------------------

- Always use the same Python interpreter for:
    - installing nnxc_tools
    - running export_nnxc.sh

  Check with:
    which python

- Passing .eqx or .json to --fx-model / --fc-model will fail.
  Always pass the prefix only.

- export_nnxc.sh is the recommended interface; calling
  export_eqx_to_fortran.py directly is discouraged for normal use.
